<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06205213 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06205213 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  LANGUAGE; EDUCATION; ORGANIZATION; MOUNTAIN-VIEW; QUOTE; HUMOR  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  In an MTV world where people have little time to read, the good folks at theSociety for the Preservation of English Language and Literature forever fightto keep the mother tongue from grammatical abuses. It is not an easy job, asproven by the fact that the language guardians from the Mountain View-basedgroup never quite run out of materials for their &quot;goof cards.&quot;;    Thefollowing samples are from a university president:  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  MONITORING LANGUAGE MANGLERSFROM A 'CREDIBILITY' RATING TO AN 'ABYSMAL'VIEW OF THE ABYSS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Today on the Peninsula  </MEMO><TEXT>     (check) &quot;Your gifts help us to do what we do very well even better.&quot;;   (check) &quot; . . . help keep learner tuition from escalating higher than theymight otherwise rise.&quot;;    Some of the more humorous errors came from allwalks of life. Montgomery Burt, a society member, found these gems in the&quot;Travellers Tales&quot; column in a newsletter of the Marlin Travel Agency inRichmond, British Columbia:;    (check) On a back door of a hotel in Tanzania:&quot;In the event of unusual fire do not continue smoking. Lie down and continuebreathing.&quot;;    (check) In the lobby of a hotel: &quot;If you wish to change money,please have your credibility ready.&quot;;    (check) An advice to maid service inYugoslavia: &quot;The flattening of underwear with pleasure is the job to thechambermaid.&quot;;    (check) Laundry in Bangkok: &quot;Drop your trousers here forbest results.&quot;;    (check) From an airline ticket office in Copenhagen: &quot;Wetake your bags and send them in all directions.&quot;;    (check) On the door of aMoscow hotel room: &quot;If this is your first visit to the USSR, you are welcometo it.&quot;;    (check) A notice in an old elevator: &quot;If you have to weigh morethan 250 pounds, kindly take up the space of two people, because this elevatorcannot take any more.&quot;;    (check) A letter from a European hotel: &quot; . . . ourrooms overlook the panoramic view of the abyss beyond our gardens and aretruly abysmal.&quot;;    To join the Society for the Preservation of EnglishLanguage and Literature, write to 1527 Gilmore St., Mountain View, CA 94040.;SOUND OF SILENCE: Organizers of the Peninsula Music Festival announced thatthe concert, scheduled for July 27 at El Camino Park, has been canceled. Theevent was to raise money for literacy programs and Palo Alto-East Palo Altoart projects. Low ticket sales forced the cancellation.;    Tickets boughtthrough BASS ticket outlets will be refunded, including service charges, atthe outlet where they were purchased. All other tickets will be refunded bythe Palo Alto recreation department at Lucie Stern Community Center. For arefund by mail, send your tickets to Peninsula Music Festival Refunds, LucieStern Community Center, 1305 Middlefield Road, Palo Alto, CA 94301. Fordetails call (415) 329-2380.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  De Tran column  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Peninsula/AM  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910723  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Tuesday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  453  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Tuesday July 23, 199100205213,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>